g="eng"><ce:para>Ferroelectric materials exhibit multifunctional properties such as piezoelectricity, nonvolatile charge, and electrooptic functions. In contrast, piezoelectric strains cannot possess these nonvolatile characteristics with the two observable different states because the generated piezoelectric strains are returned to the same positions without an applied electric field. In other words, a symmetric piezoelectric butterfly curve is expected with regard to the piezoelectric strain axis, indicating that no shape memory window is available. It is interesting to note that the shifted hysteresis loop with an asymmetric piezoelectric strain provides a potential operating source for nonvolatile piezoelectric shape memory. The origin of this imprint effect in ferroelectric materials is the internal electric field induced by electrode configurations, trapped charge, and external processes such as optical and thermal processes.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84919790876" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84919790876&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84919790876%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60012708" id="60012708"><affilname>Stanford University</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60032330" id="60032330"><affilname>Pohang University of Science and Technology</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60032624" id="60032624"><affilname>Ulsan University</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60001873" id="60001873"><affilname>Kyung Hee University</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="55786